  "prompt": "India's population is growing at an alarming rate. Why hasn't a single politician or a journalist raised the question of having strict population control laws in the country?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why population control remains a sensitive topic in India:\n\n1. Political Sensitivity:\n- Fear of alienating specific religious or community vote banks\n- Potential backlash from minority communities\n- Concerns about perceived discrimination\n\n2. Constitutional Constraints:\n- Indian Constitution guarantees reproductive rights\n- Forced population control could be seen as violation of individual rights\n\n3. Complex Social Dynamics:\n- High fertility rates linked to socio-economic factors\n- Poverty, lack of education, and limited access to family planning\n- Cultural preferences for larger families\n\n4. Previous Controversial Experiences:\n- Memories of forced sterilization during Emergency (1975-77)\n- Public resistance to coercive population control measures\n\n5. Alternative Approaches:\n- Governments preferring soft interventions like:\n  - Female education\n  - Awareness campaigns\n  - Improved healthcare access\n  - Economic incentives for smaller families\n\n6. Demographic Dividend Perspective:\n- Some experts argue young population can be economic asset\n- Focus on skill development rather than population reduction\n\n7. Lack of Political Will:\n- No significant electoral advantage in addressing population growth\n- Other immediate issues seem more pressing\n\nWhile population control is discussed, direct legal interventions remain politically challenging in India.",
